<p><a name="HIV"></a><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="4"><b>HIV testing not enough</b></font><p>

<font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">THE U.S. Center for Disease Control (CDC) recently issued a recommendation that HIV testing become part of routine medical checkups for people from ages 13 to 64. This plan seems likely to reduce the number of AIDS cases, but falls far short of what is needed to stop this devastating public health emergency.<p>
According to the CDC, over 250,000 Americans have HIV and are unaware of it. This new plan may put a dent in those numbers, but as long as 45 million Americans have no access to health coverage, this disease is not going to disappear. In fact, it is very likely because health care is unaffordable that so many don't know about their HIV status.<p>
A real program to combat AIDS would include free universal health care for everyone in the United States (immigrants included). HIV is a virus that doesn't respect race, gender, class, political persuasion or national origin. <p>
Any program that restricts detection, prevention and treatment to the subset of the public that can afford the "luxury" of health care is nothing more than a bandage for a global public health crisis.<br>
<b>Nicholas Hart,</b> Seattle<p>

